{
  "analysis": "Still 1 pixel difference at (432,300) red channel: ref=76, mine=77. I need to match the exact floating-point operation order from the disassembly. The diffuse dot product in the original computes (ld.x*n.x + precomputed_ld.y*n.y) + ld.z*n.z, while my code computes n.z*ld.z + (n.x*ld.x + n.y*ld.y). The order of addition matters for floating-point precision.",
  "plan": "Change the diffuse dot product order to match the disassembly: (n.x*ld.x + n.y*ld.y) + n.z*ld.z. Then compile, run, and compare.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "sed -i 's/n.z*ld.z+(n.x*ld.x+n.y*ld.y)/(n.x*ld.x+n.y*ld.y)+n.z*ld.z/' /app/mystery.c && grep -n 'df=' /app/mystery.c\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "gcc -static -o /app/reversed /app/mystery.c -lm && /app/mystery && cp /app/image.ppm /tmp/ref.ppm && /app/reversed && cp /app/image.ppm /tmp/mine.ppm && perl -e 'sub rp{open(F,$_[0]);<F>;<F>;<F>;my @p;while(<F>){push @p,split;}return @p;} my @r=rp(\"/tmp/ref.ppm\");my @m=rp(\"/tmp/mine.ppm\");my $n=scalar(@r);my $d=0;for my $i(0..$n-1){if($r[$i]!=$m[$i]){$d++;if($d<=10){my $px=$i/3;my $y=int($px/800);my $x=$px%800;print \"idx $i x=$x y=$y ch=\",$i%3,\" ref=$r[$i] mine=$m[$i]\\n\";}}}print \"total=$n diffs=$d\\n\";'\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}
